Question: returning a key from inner hashmap that has lowest value: :I have a nested HashMap:HashMap<String, Map<String,Integer>> map = new HashMap<>();The key for the nested map may have multiple values:{Color={Red=4, Blue=6}}I want to be able to return the key of the nested map that has the lowest value. In this case, if I gave the key Color from the outer map, I want to have Red returned. Any help is greatly appreciated.
Please using this api: Iterator.next.
Answer:
<<<api>>>: Iterator.next
<<<code>>>: 
Iterator<Map.Entry<String, Map<String,Integer>>> outerIterator = map.entrySet().iterator();
while(outerIterator.hasNext()){
    Map.Entry<String, Map<String,Integer>> outerEntry = outerIterator.next();
    Iterator<Map.Entry<String,Integer>> innerIterator = outerEntry.getValue().entrySet().iterator();
    String lowestKey = "";
    int lowestValue = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
    while(innerIterator.hasNext()){
        Map.Entry<String,Integer> innerEntry = innerIterator.next();
        if(innerEntry.getValue() < lowestValue){
            lowestValue = innerEntry.getValue();
            lowestKey = innerEntry.getKey();
        }
    }
    System.out.println("Key with lowest value for " + outerEntry.getKey() + " is: " + lowestKey);
}
<<<explanation>>>: 
This code iterates over the outer HashMap. For each entry in the outer HashMap, it creates an iterator for the inner HashMap. It then iterates over the inner HashMap, checking each entry to see if its value is less than the current lowest value. If it is, it updates the lowest value and lowest key. After going through all the entries in the inner HashMap, it prints the key with the lowest value for the current outer entry. It repeats this process for all entries in the outer HashMap.
